This is a known breaking change. Android deprecated `SOFT_INPUT_ADJUST_RESIZE` in API 30, and .NET 10 MAUI no longer supports it. Here's what to do instead:

## Option 1: Use `KeyboardAutoManagerScroll` (simplest)

This is enabled by default in .NET 9+. If you disabled it, re-enable it on your page or the specific input:

```xml
<Entry
    xmlns:android="clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.AndroidSpecific;
           assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls"
    android:Application.WindowSoftInputModeAdjust="Resize"  <!-- remove this -->
    ... />
```

Make sure you're **not** opting out anywhere:

```csharp
// Don't do this — it disables the auto-scroll behavior
Microsoft.Maui.Platform.KeyboardAutoManagerScroll.Disconnect();
```

## Option 2: Handle insets manually (full control for chat UIs)

For a chat screen, you typically want the entire layout to shrink — not just scroll. Handle Android window insets directly:

```csharp
// In your MauiProgram.cs or a custom handler
#if ANDROID
using AndroidX.Core.View;
using Microsoft.Maui.Platform;
#endif

// In your Chat page's handler or OnAppearing:
#if ANDROID
var activity = Platform.CurrentActivity;
var rootView = activity?.Window?.DecorView?.FindViewById(Android.Resource.Id.Content);

if (rootView != null)
{
    ViewCompat.SetOnApplyWindowInsetsListener(rootView, new InsetListener());
}
#endif
```

```csharp
#if ANDROID
class InsetListener : Java.Lang.Object, IOnApplyWindowInsetsListener
{
    public WindowInsetsCompat OnApplyWindowInsets(Android.Views.View v, WindowInsetsCompat insets)
    {
        var imeInsets = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.Ime());
        var navInsets = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.NavigationBars());

        // Apply bottom padding = keyboard height (or nav bar if keyboard is closed)
        int bottom = Math.Max(imeInsets.Bottom, navInsets.Bottom);
        v.SetPadding(v.PaddingLeft, v.PaddingTop, v.PaddingRight, bottom);

        return insets;
    }
}
#endif
```

## Option 3: Quick platform tweak in `AndroidManifest.xml`

If you just need the old behavior back temporarily:

```xml
<activity
    android:windowSoftInputMode="adjustPan"
    ... />
```

`adjustPan` still works and will push the whole view up, though it won't resize the layout.

---

**For a chat screen, Option 2 is recommended** — it gives you pixel-perfect control, properly resizes the message list, and works with edge-to-edge rendering in .NET 10.
